Brazilian specimens have lateral antennae that are proportionally longer than those of specimens from Australia (
San Martín 2005
) and Galápagos (
Westheide 1974
), and the bayonet chaetae of chaetigers 1–3 are longer. The specimen from Cuba has up to six bayonet chaetae in each parapodium of chaetigers 1–3 , with blades ca. 4 µm long; from chaetiger 4 onwards, each parapodium bears a single bayonet chaeta with a blade 5–8 µm long and 2–3 chaetae with blades fused to shafts; that specimen has blades of the bayonet chaetae relatively shorter than those of the Brazilian specimens.
